{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-838e4defc3e90711", "type": "tool_result", "content": "2621 paper_2607.15694.txt\nThis work has been submitted to the IEEE for possible publication. Copyright may be transferred without notice, after which this version may no longer be\naccessible.\n\n1\n\nA Geometry-Limited Identification Floor and Its\nConsequences for Voice-Clone Attribution in\nProfessional Voice Actors\n\narXiv:2607.15694v1 [eess.AS] 17 Jul 2026\n\nShuhei Kato\n\nAbstract—A voice actor’s voice is their asset, and AI cloning\ndirectly threatens it. The natural defense flags the enrolled actor\nwhose embedding similarity to a suspect recording crosses a\nthreshold. We show it fails where it is most needed: trained\nvoices crowd the embedding space, and each actor performs many\nstyles. On 1,168 Japanese voice actors (56,568 segments, ~63 h), a\nmisidentification floor survives calibration, score normalization,\nand discriminative re-ranking (linear and nonlinear, including\nPLDA): the residual is a limit of the embedding geometry, not\nof the back-ends we evaluate. The best ensemble still leaves\n~2.6 % closed-set misidentification, several-fold above matched\ncontrols; session-disjoint, re-ranking lowers the floor only to\n13.0 %. The same crowding drives false attribution: on a generic\nEnglish encoder, roughly half the clones of non-enrolled people\nfalsely accuse an enrolled actor, while — by a separate realvs-synthetic shift — 32 % of Seed-VC clones of enrolled targets\nare missed at the same threshold; one operating point couples\nthe two, and none escapes both. A domain-matched, voice-actortrained encoder mitigates substantially (a four-fold gender gap\nvanishes; wrongful misattribution falls to 1.5–10 %), but does\nnot remove the floor. Controls (codec, channel, vocoder, content)\nsupport reading the miss rate as a real-versus-synthetic covariate\nshift, not missing speaker information. Fixed-threshold clone\nattribution is thus unreliable here, and on a generic encoder\nunfair. Robust attribution must extend spoofing-aware speaker\nverification to open-set 1:N (anti-spoofing gate, domain-matched\nencoder, per-speaker calibration, abstain option), and even then\nsupports detection, not autonomous enforcement.\nIndex Terms—Speaker recognition, speaker verification,\nspeaker embedding, voice conversion, anti-spoofing, audio deepfakes, hubness, score calibration, algorithmic fairness, biometric\nidentification.\n\nI. I NTRODUCTION\nAI voice cloning generates a target speaker from seconds of\naudio [1]. For a professional voice actor, whose voice is their\nlivelihood, this is an existential threat [2] — one the profession\nitself has organized against, most visibly in the “NOMORE無\n断生成AI” (No More Unauthorized Generative AI) campaign\nlaunched in 2024 by 26 professional Japanese voice actors [3].\nThe natural technology-based defense is to make the machine\ntell voices apart: embed a suspect utterance, compare it to\nenrolled actors, and flag actor X when the similarity to X\ncrosses a threshold — reducing “Is this an unauthorized clone\nof X?” to a 1 : N decision. This paper shows that the machine\nis worst at exactly the voices of this profession (Fig. 1).\nTwo scenarios make the stakes concrete. (1) Wrongful\naccusation. A non-actor clones their own (or a friend’s) voice;\nCorresponding author: Shuhei Kato (e-mail: shuhei@shuheikato.info).\nThe author is an independent researcher in Tokyo, Japan.\n\nit happens to resemble some enrolled actor B, and an objectivemetric detector points at B. As of the U.S. Copyright Office’s\nJuly 2024 review [4], no U.S. federal statute directly addresses\nunauthorized voice replication and the main remedies are\ncivil; at the state level, Tennessee’s ELVIS Act (2024) [5]\nextended that state’s existing civil-and-misdemeanor right of\npublicity to voice and to tools whose primary purpose is\nvoice cloning — liability attaching to unauthorized use and\ndistribution rather than to cloning as such. In Japan, where\nthe actors we study work, no statute addresses it either: the\npublicity right is case-law only (Pink Lady v. Kobunsha, Sup.\nCt., Feb. 2, 2012 [6], framed around the customer-drawing\npower of a persona) and its application to voice is untested\nin court. Either way, a civil claim resting on this metric\nwould be damaging. A sharper variant: even a company that\nlegitimately licenses actor A and clones A with consent\ncan be sued by an unrelated actor B the clone happens to\nresemble, the metric naming B would be damaging evidence.\n(2) Unprotected victim. Conversely, an actor’s voice is cloned\nwithout permission, but the synthesizer is mediocre: the result\naudibly sounds like the victim to a human ear, yet its\nobjective similarity falls below the threshold, so the victim\ncannot be protected. Loosening the threshold to fix this then\nfloods scenario (1) with false accusations. These failures are\nnot independent bugs: they are the two sides of one operating\npoint (threshold) — the false-accept/false-reject trade-off.\nWorse, falling below the threshold is not proof of non-identity\neither — by the real-synthetic shift of Section IV-D, even\na clone derived from the person themselves can fall below\nit — so the metric hands a decisive claim to neither side.\nAnd because the error’s source lies in the embedding-space\ngeometry, adjusting the threshold alone cannot resolve both\nat once. This is the danger of fixed-threshold attribution that\nthe rest of the paper quantifies. No court or platform runs\nthis exact procedure today; we quantify the failure mode any\nnaive similarity-threshold system would inherit, and show that\nthresholding alone cannot make it safe.\nOur contribution is to show what these effects produce when\nthey compound in one domain: where both the inter-speaker\ndensity (how close the trained voices are) and the domainintrinsic intra-speaker style range (narration, dialogue, character voices) are high, the rank-1 identification error —\nclosed-set identification that names the query’s nearestneighbor speaker (Section IV-A) — is limited by the\nembedding geometry, not by scoring, with concrete, partly\nmitigable consequences for clone attribution and fairness. The\n\n\f2\n\nFig. 1. The failure this paper quantifies. In the dense embedding space of professional voice actors (left), a similarity-threshold detector fails both ways at one\noperating point (right): a clone of an enrolled actor is pushed below the real-calibrated threshold τ by the synthetic-vs-real shift (missed), while a clone of a\nnon-enrolled person lands on an innocent enrolled actor above τ (wrongful accusation). Raising τ trades one harm for the other; the limit is the embedding\ngeometry, not the threshold. Rates are for the generic English encoder (Section IV-D).\n\ningredients are individually known; their joint effect in the\nhigh-density professional voice-actor domain is not. That a\nraw cosine threshold is suboptimal has been clear since the\nera of i-vectors and probabilistic linear discriminant analysis\n(PLDA) [7], [8], [9], [10] — the reason adaptive symmetric\nnormalization (AS-norm) [11] and calibration [12] exist —\nas have hubness in high-dimensional embeddings [13] and\nthe fact that test-side score normalization such as T-norm\n[14] is a monotone transform of each query’s scores, moving\nthe threshold but not the neighbor ranking [11]. AS-norm\nadditionally carries an enrollment-side term whose cohort\nstatistics differ across speakers, so it can re-rank neighbors — empirically, only slightly here. The forensic-voicecomparison literature has likewise long studied how the choice\nand density of the relevant population affect likelihood-ratio\nevidence [15], [16], [17]. Because no monotone recalibration\ncan move a rank-1/argmax decision, the load-bearing test is\nnot calibration but discriminative re-ranking that genuinely\nreorders neighbors: linear discriminant analysis (LDA) [18],\nwithin-class covariance normalization (WCCN) [19], and a\ntwo-covariance PLDA log-likelihood ratio (LLR) [9], [10],\n[20], fit by moments and cross-checked by an expectationmaximization (EM) refit (Appendix A). These only partly\nreduce the residual misidentification floor and hub structure;\nthe remainder is a property of the geometry itself.\nContributions.\n\n3. Confound control (codec, recording channel, agency\nstudio) and matched comparison to control populations\n(JVS [21], Common Voice JA [22]), showing the domain is genuinely harder, driven partly by inter-speaker\nproximity and partly by intra-speaker style range (their\nrelative shares not fully separated; Section IV-C).\n4. A defensive clone probe quantifying missed attribution\n(an attribution-recall miss, not a countermeasure falsenegative) and wrongful accusation at deployment scale,\nwith a clone-geometry analysis attributing the failure to\na synthetic-vs-real covariate shift, not lack of identity\ninformation (Section IV-D).\n5. Five cross-cutting findings (A–E): the synthetic-real shift\n(A), a gender fairness gap mitigable by a domainmatched encoder (B), style-dependent misattribution\nrisk (C), the cost of a single operating point (D), and\nthe community/reciprocity structure of confusions (E)\n— each worse for the generic English encoder and\nmitigated by a Japanese voice-actor-trained one (Sections IV-D and IV-E).\nTogether, these yield concrete design requirements for\nanyone deploying voice-clone attribution or training-datamisuse detection — a spoofing-aware, open-set attribution\npipeline with a domain-matched encoder, per-speaker calibration, and an abstain-and-human-review option (Section V).\n\n1. A provenance-tracked, reproducible corpus and pipeline\nfor voice-actor embedding geometry, with a documented\ncoverage funnel (Section III).\n2. Across eight encoders and two ensembles, a closedset rank-1 identification analysis showing a misidentification floor that survives discriminative reranking (LDA, WCCN, and a two-covariance\nPLDA LLR — moment-fit and EM alike), not\nmerely calibration, together with consistently positive\nbut multiple-comparison-fragile k-occurrence hubness\n(Benjamini–Hochberg-significant, Holm-nonsignificant;\nSections IV-A and IV-B).\n\nII. R ELATED WORK\nSpeaker embeddings and verification. The standard encoders based on the time-delay neural network (TDNN) [23]\nthat extract a fixed-length speaker-identity vector from an\nutterance are the x-vector [24] and ECAPA-TDNN [25]. More\nrecently, self-supervised models (WavLM [26], HuBERT [27])\nand newer architectures (CAM++ [28], ReDimNet [29], and\nthe related ERes2Net [30]) have driven the equal error rate\n(EER) on VoxCeleb [31] below 1 %. In deployment, raw cosine similarity is not used directly for a threshold decision; instead, a PLDA back-end [7], [9], [10], AS-norm [11], [32], and\ncalibration [12] make thresholds transferable across recording\n\n\f3\n\nconditions. AS-norm normalizes each query’s score relative to\nits similarity distribution within a cohort of unrelated speakers;\nwe evaluate it under this normalization. The discriminative\ncore of PLDA — a two-covariance PLDA LLR — is one of\nthe neighbor-reordering re-rankers in our suite (Section IV-B).\nThe main tables use a moment/scatter fit, whose size-weighted\nbetween-class scatter is a biased (over-)estimate (Appendix A).\nTo rule the estimator out as the bottleneck, we also refit the\nsame model by EM/maximum-likelihood (ML) — the canonical construction for the length-normalized TDNN encoders\n(x-vector, ECAPA-TDNN, CAM++, ReDimNet) — on the\nsame splits. Closed-set misidentification moves by at most 0.4\npercentage points (pp) on every properly-configured encoder\n(Appendix A), so the residual floor is not an artifact of the\nmoment fit. A full generative PLDA back-end over the selfsupervised front-ends (WavLM, JP-HuBERT) remains future\nwork; those are diagnostic probes in any case (Section IV-A).\nHubness. In high-dimensional nearest-neighbor spaces, a\nfew points become the nearest neighbor of disproportionately\nmany others — hubs [13]. Hubness is conventionally measured\nby the skewness of the k-occurrence distribution (how many\ntimes each point is another’s nearest neighbor), and reduced\nby centering, mutual proximity [33], non-iterative contextual\ndissimilarity measure (NICDM) [34], or cross-domain similarity local scaling (CSLS) [35] — our “centering helps WavLM”\nis one example. Our main results use centering and AS-norm,\nShell cwd was reset to /inspire/qb-ilm/project/video-generation/chenxie-25019/hyr/iHateTheWorld555.github.io", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "f154d6d5-43c7-4ae8-9b50-952e770c6f4c", "uuid": "f58bc652-b730-435d-9f41-7b26da1253f6", "timestamp": "2026-07-20T09:23:56.388Z", "tool_use_result": {"stdout": "2621 paper_2607.15694.txt\nThis work has been submitted to the IEEE for possible publication. Copyright may be transferred without notice, after which this version may no longer be\naccessible.\n\n1\n\nA Geometry-Limited Identification Floor and Its\nConsequences for Voice-Clone Attribution in\nProfessional Voice Actors\n\narXiv:2607.15694v1 [eess.AS] 17 Jul 2026\n\nShuhei Kato\n\nAbstract—A voice actor’s voice is their asset, and AI cloning\ndirectly threatens it. The natural defense flags the enrolled actor\nwhose embedding similarity to a suspect recording crosses a\nthreshold. We show it fails where it is most needed: trained\nvoices crowd the embedding space, and each actor performs many\nstyles. On 1,168 Japanese voice actors (56,568 segments, ~63 h), a\nmisidentification floor survives calibration, score normalization,\nand discriminative re-ranking (linear and nonlinear, including\nPLDA): the residual is a limit of the embedding geometry, not\nof the back-ends we evaluate. The best ensemble still leaves\n~2.6 % closed-set misidentification, several-fold above matched\ncontrols; session-disjoint, re-ranking lowers the floor only to\n13.0 %. The same crowding drives false attribution: on a generic\nEnglish encoder, roughly half the clones of non-enrolled people\nfalsely accuse an enrolled actor, while — by a separate realvs-synthetic shift — 32 % of Seed-VC clones of enrolled targets\nare missed at the same threshold; one operating point couples\nthe two, and none escapes both. A domain-matched, voice-actortrained encoder mitigates substantially (a four-fold gender gap\nvanishes; wrongful misattribution falls to 1.5–10 %), but does\nnot remove the floor. Controls (codec, channel, vocoder, content)\nsupport reading the miss rate as a real-versus-synthetic covariate\nshift, not missing speaker information. Fixed-threshold clone\nattribution is thus unreliable here, and on a generic encoder\nunfair. Robust attribution must extend spoofing-aware speaker\nverification to open-set 1:N (anti-spoofing gate, domain-matched\nencoder, per-speaker calibration, abstain option), and even then\nsupports detection, not autonomous enforcement.\nIndex Terms—Speaker recognition, speaker verification,\nspeaker embedding, voice conversion, anti-spoofing, audio deepfakes, hubness, score calibration, algorithmic fairness, biometric\nidentification.\n\nI. I NTRODUCTION\nAI voice cloning generates a target speaker from seconds of\naudio [1]. For a professional voice actor, whose voice is their\nlivelihood, this is an existential threat [2] — one the profession\nitself has organized against, most visibly in the “NOMORE無\n断生成AI” (No More Unauthorized Generative AI) campaign\nlaunched in 2024 by 26 professional Japanese voice actors [3].\nThe natural technology-based defense is to make the machine\ntell voices apart: embed a suspect utterance, compare it to\nenrolled actors, and flag actor X when the similarity to X\ncrosses a threshold — reducing “Is this an unauthorized clone\nof X?” to a 1 : N decision. This paper shows that the machine\nis worst at exactly the voices of this profession (Fig. 1).\nTwo scenarios make the stakes concrete. (1) Wrongful\naccusation. A non-actor clones their own (or a friend’s) voice;\nCorresponding author: Shuhei Kato (e-mail: shuhei@shuheikato.info).\nThe author is an independent researcher in Tokyo, Japan.\n\nit happens to resemble some enrolled actor B, and an objectivemetric detector points at B. As of the U.S. Copyright Office’s\nJuly 2024 review [4], no U.S. federal statute directly addresses\nunauthorized voice replication and the main remedies are\ncivil; at the state level, Tennessee’s ELVIS Act (2024) [5]\nextended that state’s existing civil-and-misdemeanor right of\npublicity to voice and to tools whose primary purpose is\nvoice cloning — liability attaching to unauthorized use and\ndistribution rather than to cloning as such. In Japan, where\nthe actors we study work, no statute addresses it either: the\npublicity right is case-law only (Pink Lady v. Kobunsha, Sup.\nCt., Feb. 2, 2012 [6], framed around the customer-drawing\npower of a persona) and its application to voice is untested\nin court. Either way, a civil claim resting on this metric\nwould be damaging. A sharper variant: even a company that\nlegitimately licenses actor A and clones A with consent\ncan be sued by an unrelated actor B the clone happens to\nresemble, the metric naming B would be damaging evidence.\n(2) Unprotected victim. Conversely, an actor’s voice is cloned\nwithout permission, but the synthesizer is mediocre: the result\naudibly sounds like the victim to a human ear, yet its\nobjective similarity falls below the threshold, so the victim\ncannot be protected. Loosening the threshold to fix this then\nfloods scenario (1) with false accusations. These failures are\nnot independent bugs: they are the two sides of one operating\npoint (threshold) — the false-accept/false-reject trade-off.\nWorse, falling below the threshold is not proof of non-identity\neither — by the real-synthetic shift of Section IV-D, even\na clone derived from the person themselves can fall below\nit — so the metric hands a decisive claim to neither side.\nAnd because the error’s source lies in the embedding-space\ngeometry, adjusting the threshold alone cannot resolve both\nat once. This is the danger of fixed-threshold attribution that\nthe rest of the paper quantifies. No court or platform runs\nthis exact procedure today; we quantify the failure mode any\nnaive similarity-threshold system would inherit, and show that\nthresholding alone cannot make it safe.\nOur contribution is to show what these effects produce when\nthey compound in one domain: where both the inter-speaker\ndensity (how close the trained voices are) and the domainintrinsic intra-speaker style range (narration, dialogue, character voices) are high, the rank-1 identification error —\nclosed-set identification that names the query’s nearestneighbor speaker (Section IV-A) — is limited by the\nembedding geometry, not by scoring, with concrete, partly\nmitigable consequences for clone attribution and fairness. The\n\n\f2\n\nFig. 1. The failure this paper quantifies. In the dense embedding space of professional voice actors (left), a similarity-threshold detector fails both ways at one\noperating point (right): a clone of an enrolled actor is pushed below the real-calibrated threshold τ by the synthetic-vs-real shift (missed), while a clone of a\nnon-enrolled person lands on an innocent enrolled actor above τ (wrongful accusation). Raising τ trades one harm for the other; the limit is the embedding\ngeometry, not the threshold. Rates are for the generic English encoder (Section IV-D).\n\ningredients are individually known; their joint effect in the\nhigh-density professional voice-actor domain is not. That a\nraw cosine threshold is suboptimal has been clear since the\nera of i-vectors and probabilistic linear discriminant analysis\n(PLDA) [7], [8], [9], [10] — the reason adaptive symmetric\nnormalization (AS-norm) [11] and calibration [12] exist —\nas have hubness in high-dimensional embeddings [13] and\nthe fact that test-side score normalization such as T-norm\n[14] is a monotone transform of each query’s scores, moving\nthe threshold but not the neighbor ranking [11]. AS-norm\nadditionally carries an enrollment-side term whose cohort\nstatistics differ across speakers, so it can re-rank neighbors — empirically, only slightly here. The forensic-voicecomparison literature has likewise long studied how the choice\nand density of the relevant population affect likelihood-ratio\nevidence [15], [16], [17]. Because no monotone recalibration\ncan move a rank-1/argmax decision, the load-bearing test is\nnot calibration but discriminative re-ranking that genuinely\nreorders neighbors: linear discriminant analysis (LDA) [18],\nwithin-class covariance normalization (WCCN) [19], and a\ntwo-covariance PLDA log-likelihood ratio (LLR) [9], [10],\n[20], fit by moments and cross-checked by an expectationmaximization (EM) refit (Appendix A). These only partly\nreduce the residual misidentification floor and hub structure;\nthe remainder is a property of the geometry itself.\nContributions.\n\n3. Confound control (codec, recording channel, agency\nstudio) and matched comparison to control populations\n(JVS [21], Common Voice JA [22]), showing the domain is genuinely harder, driven partly by inter-speaker\nproximity and partly by intra-speaker style range (their\nrelative shares not fully separated; Section IV-C).\n4. A defensive clone probe quantifying missed attribution\n(an attribution-recall miss, not a countermeasure falsenegative) and wrongful accusation at deployment scale,\nwith a clone-geometry analysis attributing the failure to\na synthetic-vs-real covariate shift, not lack of identity\ninformation (Section IV-D).\n5. Five cross-cutting findings (A–E): the synthetic-real shift\n(A), a gender fairness gap mitigable by a domainmatched encoder (B), style-dependent misattribution\nrisk (C), the cost of a single operating point (D), and\nthe community/reciprocity structure of confusions (E)\n— each worse for the generic English encoder and\nmitigated by a Japanese voice-actor-trained one (Sections IV-D and IV-E).\nTogether, these yield concrete design requirements for\nanyone deploying voice-clone attribution or training-datamisuse detection — a spoofing-aware, open-set attribution\npipeline with a domain-matched encoder, per-speaker calibration, and an abstain-and-human-review option (Section V).\n\n1. A provenance-tracked, reproducible corpus and pipeline\nfor voice-actor embedding geometry, with a documented\ncoverage funnel (Section III).\n2. Across eight encoders and two ensembles, a closedset rank-1 identification analysis showing a misidentification floor that survives discriminative reranking (LDA, WCCN, and a two-covariance\nPLDA LLR — moment-fit and EM alike), not\nmerely calibration, together with consistently positive\nbut multiple-comparison-fragile k-occurrence hubness\n(Benjamini–Hochberg-significant, Holm-nonsignificant;\nSections IV-A and IV-B).\n\nII. R ELATED WORK\nSpeaker embeddings and verification. The standard encoders based on the time-delay neural network (TDNN) [23]\nthat extract a fixed-length speaker-identity vector from an\nutterance are the x-vector [24] and ECAPA-TDNN [25]. More\nrecently, self-supervised models (WavLM [26], HuBERT [27])\nand newer architectures (CAM++ [28], ReDimNet [29], and\nthe related ERes2Net [30]) have driven the equal error rate\n(EER) on VoxCeleb [31] below 1 %. In deployment, raw cosine similarity is not used directly for a threshold decision; instead, a PLDA back-end [7], [9], [10], AS-norm [11], [32], and\ncalibration [12] make thresholds transferable across recording\n\n\f3\n\nconditions. AS-norm normalizes each query’s score relative to\nits similarity distribution within a cohort of unrelated speakers;\nwe evaluate it under this normalization. The discriminative\ncore of PLDA — a two-covariance PLDA LLR — is one of\nthe neighbor-reordering re-rankers in our suite (Section IV-B).\nThe main tables use a moment/scatter fit, whose size-weighted\nbetween-class scatter is a biased (over-)estimate (Appendix A).\nTo rule the estimator out as the bottleneck, we also refit the\nsame model by EM/maximum-likelihood (ML) — the canonical construction for the length-normalized TDNN encoders\n(x-vector, ECAPA-TDNN, CAM++, ReDimNet) — on the\nsame splits. Closed-set misidentification moves by at most 0.4\npercentage points (pp) on every properly-configured encoder\n(Appendix A), so the residual floor is not an artifact of the\nmoment fit. A full generative PLDA back-end over the selfsupervised front-ends (WavLM, JP-HuBERT) remains future\nwork; those are diagnostic probes in any case (Section IV-A).\nHubness. In high-dimensional nearest-neighbor spaces, a\nfew points become the nearest neighbor of disproportionately\nmany others — hubs [13]. Hubness is conventionally measured\nby the skewness of the k-occurrence distribution (how many\ntimes each point is another’s nearest neighbor), and reduced\nby centering, mutual proximity [33], non-iterative contextual\ndissimilarity measure (NICDM) [34], or cross-domain similarity local scaling (CSLS) [35] — our “centering helps WavLM”\nis one example. Our main results use centering and AS-norm,", "stderr": "\nShell cwd was reset to /inspire/qb-ilm/project/video-generation/chenxie-25019/hyr/iHateTheWorld555.github.io", "interrupted": false, "isImage": false, "noOutputExpected": false}}
