{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-b8ac66af5d30b48e", "type": "tool_result", "content": "is one example. Our main results use centering and AS-norm,\nbut we also ran a systematic comparison of these methods\n(cf. [36]): on the same query→centroid rank-1 protocol, comparing raw cosine, centering, CSLS (k=10), empirical mutual\nproximity [33], and NICDM (k=10) across four encoders\n(ECAPA-TDNN, animeva, WavLM, SV-4; animeva is our\ndomain-matched Japanese voice-actor ECAPA-TDNN, defined\nin Section III), no method improves misidentification by more\nthan ~0.3 points over raw cosine (local scaling hurts, by up\nto 5.8 points), and even mutual proximity — which flattens\nthe hub structure best (e.g. animeva k-occurrence skewness\n0.75→0.28) — leaves misidentification essentially unchanged.\nHubness can be reduced while the error floor does not move:\ndirect evidence that the floor is a property of the geometry,\nnot an artifact of hubness. Our claim is that a floor remains\nafter these standard reductions, not that the reductions are\nineffective.\nVoice privacy/anonymization. Our defensive setting is adjacent to speaker anonymization and voice privacy work [37],\nwhich deliberately suppresses speaker identity. We measure\nthe converse: how reliably can identity be attributed to a\nsynthetic clone?\nAnti-spoofing and spoofing-aware speaker verification\n(SASV). ASVspoof [38], [39] addresses detection of synthetic\nand spoofed speech, with tandem CM–ASV operation assessed\nby the tandem detection cost function (t-DCF) [40]; SASV\n[41] integrates these countermeasures with speaker verification, and the latest edition, ASVspoof 5 [42], folds SASV\nevaluation into the challenge at crowdsourced scale. The\nclosest existing resource to our threat setting is SpoofCeleb\n[43], which trains 23 text-to-speech (TTS) systems on in-thewild speech of 1,251 real VoxCeleb1 speakers and benchmarks\ndeepfake detection and SASV against that real enrolled pop-\n\nulation — still as a per-trial binary decision. A known weakness: countermeasures generalize poorly to unseen synthesis\nmethods [44]. Our task — attributing a clone to a real speaker’s\nidentity in an open set — extends SASV’s target/non-targetplus-spoof binary decision to 1 : N -way attribution. A twoparty dispute in which the suspected target actor is already\nnamed may reduce to 1 : 1 verification; even then, the\nsame real-synthetic shift, calibration-transfer, and per-speaker\nthreshold-spread problems apply (Sections IV-B and IV-D).\nWe adopt the more general 1 : N framing, subsuming the\nscreening use case — matching audio of unknown origin\nagainst a roster — that motivates this paper. This 1 : N\ndirection distinguishes our study from the known vulnerability\nof 1 : 1 verification to cloned audio (an impostor clone falsely\naccepted against its claimed target): our object is not threshold\nplacement but which of N real actors a clone is attributed to,\nand a floor on that decision that survives discriminative reranking. Existing large-gallery open-set identification benchmarks [45] target the general population; our contribution\nis that the difficulty and the attribution floor are driven by\nthe domain-intrinsic inter-speaker proximity and intra-speaker\nstyle range of the trained professional voices, which are largely\nabsent in such corpora.\nDeepfake source attribution. A separate line of work attributes generated audio to the model that produced it (vocoder\nfingerprints [46], source tracing [47]), and the recent sourceverification wave asks whether two synthetic tracks share a\ngenerator (SV-inspired but generator-level) [48]. All of this\nis generator/model attribution; at the speaker level, Cai et\nal. [49] show the source speaker behind a voice-conversion\nattack remains identifiable from the converted audio. Our\nquestion is orthogonal to both: which target real actor a\nsingle clone is attributed to, over a roster of real speakers.\nWe do not evaluate source-attribution methods; as a side\nobservation, Section IV-D reports that in a speaker-embedding\nspace, clustering by synthesizer is weak relative to clustering\nby speaker — we make no claim about what dedicated sourceattribution methods can achieve.\nFairness in speaker recognition. Demographic disparities\nin speaker recognition are documented [50]. We show a gender\ndisparity consistent with originating in the encoder’s training\ndomain and language, and removed by a domain-matched\nmodel.\nJapanese/voice-actor speech. For controls and a domainmatched encoder, we use JVS [21], Common Voice [22],\nJTubeSpeech [51], and animeva [52], an ECAPA-TDNN\ntrained on Japanese voice-actor speech (“animeva” is our\nshorthand, defined in Section III). For clone generation, we\nuse the zero-shot voice-conversion model Seed-VC [53] (v2\nrelease; a conditional-flow-matching (CFM) path with an\nautoregressive component, official default AR/CFM checkpoints, 30 sampling steps), the zero-shot TTS system GPTSoVITS [54] (run reference-only, no per-speaker fine-tuning),\nwhich spans two architecture lines — an incremental\nv1/v2 line with a high-fidelity v2ProPlus refinement, and\na newer reference-faithful v3/v4 line — each run with\nits official pretrained checkpoint pair (v1: s2G488k.pth,\nv2: s2G2333k.pth, v2ProPlus: s2Gv2ProPlus.pth, v3:\n\n\f4\n\ns2Gv3.pth, v4: s2Gv4.pth, with the corresponding default text-to-semantic (T2S) models), and the zero-shot TTS\nsystem Irodori-TTS [55] (Irodori-TTS-500M-v3, with the\nSemantic-DACVAE-Japanese-32dim codec [56]) — the latter\ntwo are public systems without academic papers, selected\nas representative Japanese-capable zero-shot synthesis; their\nfidelity is verified internally via the speaker-similarity measurements in Section IV-D, and because these systems evolve\nrapidly, exact model IDs and commits are released with the\nprovenance records of Section VI.\nIII. DATA AND PIPELINE\nRegistry (Phase 0a). We archive the seigura.com voiceactor directory [57] (声優名鑑, the Seiyu Grand Prix directory; operator Imagica Infos Co., Ltd.; URL and access dates\nin the references and provenance log). It lists 1,839 speaker\nentries across 255 agencies (1,838 distinct normalized names\n— one name maps to two entries; Section VII dedup), with\neach actor’s name, agency, and credited works, but no audio.\nThis registry is the denominator for our coverage. Every fetch\nis logged with its provenance (URL, UTC timestamp, SHA256).\nAudio (Phase 0b). We collect agency audio through peragency adapters — each agency’s site exposes samples differently, so each needs its own scraper: we enumerate the\ntalent roster, download each talent’s published samples (multiple speaking styles per talent), and match them back to\nregistry actors by normalized name. Adapters exist for the\n45 highest-actor-count agencies — ~18 % of the 255 registry\nagencies but ~64 % of registry actors, because agency size is\nheavily skewed; the remaining ~82 % are a long tail of a few\nactors each, left un-adapted at the manual per-site cost of a\nnew adapter (hence a selection bias toward larger agencies,\nSection VII). For freelance actors we use identity-verified\nofficial personal sites and official YouTube channels. “Agencyaffiliated” means having a registry agency field other than\n“freelance” (a one-person agency counts). This yields 1,103\nagency-affiliated actors (7,128 files) plus 71 freelance actors\n(277 files) — 1,174 actors in total.\nPreprocessing (Phase 0c). We standardize everything to\n16 kHz mono, remove silence with energy-based voice-activity\ndetection (VAD; librosa [58] effects.split, threshold\n30 dB below the reference level), and split into consecutive\nfixed 4 s windows, retaining a trailing remainder only if ≥3 s\n(so segments span 3–4 s) — the cut boundaries are mechanical,\nunrelated to sentence boundaries; speaker embeddings capture\nidentity content-independently, and the same segmentation is\napplied to every encoder and control population, so comparisons remain fair. 24 source files failed decoding or were\nemptied by VAD, and speakers left with zero usable segments\nwere dropped, giving a final corpus of 56,568 segments /\n1,168 speakers (1,103 agency + 65 freelance) / ~63 h. Each\nsegment carries a provenance back-pointer to its source and a\nrecording_source label. Coverage against the registry is\n1,168/1,839 = 63.5 %. The 671 uncollected actors are mostly\naffiliated with smaller agencies for which no scraper adapter\nwas built (511 actors — we built adapters for 45 of the\n\nregistry’s 255 agencies), plus freelance sources that could not\nbe captured (e.g. embedded players); this agency-side selection\nbias is discussed under generalization limits in Section VII.\nEncoders. The six base encoders are: x-vector [24] and\nECAPA-TDNN [25] (both English / VoxCeleb); WavLM-baseplus-sv [26] (English self-supervised model with a verification head); CAM++ [28] (Chinese; ModelScope checkpoint\ntrained on ~200k Mandarin speakers); ReDimNet-b2 [29]\n(English); and a layer-mean of Japanese HuBERT [59] (a\nJapanese self-supervised probe trained on the ReazonSpeech\nTV-broadcast corpus [60]). For language/domain controls,\nwe add two Japanese speaker verification models, referred\nto throughout by short names of our own: jxvector (the\nxvector_jtubespeech model, trained on JTubeSpeech)\n[61] and animeva (the anime_speaker_embedding\nmodel, an ECAPA-TDNN trained on ~989 Japanese voice\nactors) [52]; an overlap audit by name-matching against its\ntraining set’s published Visual Novel Database (VNDB) [62]\nvoice-actor metadata (Section IV-E) finds 21 % of our corpus\nin its training set, but its advantage holds on the heldout 79 %. animeva shares the ECAPA-TDNN architecture;\nthroughout, “ECAPA-TDNN” unqualified denotes the generic\nEnglish/VoxCeleb model, and the domain-matched model\nis always “animeva”. The two ensembles use embeddinglevel fusion: we concatenate each model’s L2-normalized\nembedding and renormalize, so the cosine similarity of the\nconcatenated vector equals the mean of the per-model cosine\nsimilarities (SV-4 bundles the four verification models; all-6\nbundles all six). This is deliberately a simple mean-pooling\nbaseline, not a novel fusion method — one of the mitigations\nwe test. Stronger fusion does not lower the floor, so we keep\nthe simple fixed-weight mean-pool (Table VII).\nLegal/ethics. Collection and analysis were conducted entirely within Japan under Article 30-4 (information analysis)\nof the Japanese Copyright Act [63], subject to that Article’s\nproviso, which we assess in Section VI; no audio is redistributed, and the clones are used only for the measurements in\nthis paper (no distribution, service offering, or impersonation;\nSection VI, including other jurisdictions).\nIV. R ESULTS\nA. Raw geometry: high accuracy, thin margins\nThe strong encoders look excellent, which is exactly the\nproblem: high rank-1 accuracy coexists with a large mass\nof queries decided by a hair. Table I reports raw-cosine\ngeometry across all eight encoders and the two embeddinglevel ensembles. Rank-1 accuracy — the fraction of queries\nwhose nearest neighbor is the correct speaker — is high\nfor the strong encoders (CAM++ and ReDimNet at 92.6 %,\nensembles at ~95 %, domain-matched animeva at 97.3 %), and\nevery encoder exhibits positive k-occurrence hubness skew.\nThe confound and control-population comparisons (Section IV-C) focus on representative encoders spanning the\nweak/strong and generic/domain-matched extremes (generic\nECAPA-TDNN, domain-matched animeva, SV-4 ensemble).\nEven at high rank-1 accuracy, many queries are decided by\na thin margin. Define the critical margin as the fraction of\n\n\f5\n\nTABLE I\nR AW- COSINE GEOMETRY PER ENCODER AND ENSEMBLE ( NO NORMALIZATION ): RANK -1 IDENTIFICATION ACCURACY, MISIDENTIFICATION RATE\n( MARGIN < 0), AND k- OCCURRENCE HUBNESS SKEW. T HIS IS A closed-set SETTING ( EVERY QUERY ’ S TRUE SPEAKER IS ENROLLED , NO REJECT OPTION );\nRANK -1 COUNTS STRICTLY- POSITIVE - MARGIN QUERIES AND MIS ID STRICTLY- NEGATIVE , SO MIS ID = 1 − RANK -1 up to zero-margin ties — WHICH\nFALL IN NEITHER AND ACCOUNT FOR THE SMALL ≤0.2 PERCENTAGE - POINT ( PP ) SHORTFALL IN THE ENSEMBLE ROWS . T HE TWO COLUMNS ARE\nCOMPLEMENTARY VIEWS OF THE SAME QUANTITY, SHOWN TOGETHER FOR READABILITY. T HE REJECT- CAPABLE OPERATING METRICS — STILL MATED ,\nI . E . NOT NON - TARGET- TESTED — ARE THE 1 : N EER OF S ECTION IV-B AND THE THRESHOLD - CONDITIONED CLONE ATTRIBUTION OF S ECTION IV-D.\nEncoder\n\nRank-1\n\nmisID\n\nHubness skew\n\nx-vector (EN/VoxCeleb)\nECAPA-TDNN (EN/VoxCeleb)\nWavLM-base-plus-sv (EN)\nCAM++ (ZH)\nReDimNet-b2 (EN)\nJP-HuBERT (layer-mean)\njxvector (JTubeSpeech)\nanimeva (JP voice-actor)\nensemble SV-4\nensemble all-6\n\n80.0 %\n86.7 %\n27.3 %\n92.6 %\n92.6 %\n65.9 %\n69.4 %\n97.3 %\n95.2 %\n95.0 %\n\n20.0 %\n13.3 %\n72.7 %\n7.4 %\n7.4 %\n34.1 %\n30.6 %\n2.7 %\n4.6 %\n4.9 %\n\n3.6\n2.5\n1.4\n2.2\n2.2\n1.9\n1.5\n2.2\n2.4\n2.2\n\nqueries for which |Ssame − Sdiff | < 0.02, where Ssame is the\nhighest-cosine score to the correct same speaker and Sdiff that\nto the most confusable different speaker. The 0.02 is a diagnostic cutoff on the raw-cosine margin scale; for the strong verification encoders, the conclusion is stable across cutoffs 0.005–\n0.05 (protocol in Appendix A). The absolute cutoff is not\ncomparable across encoders: x-vector, jxvector, and WavLM\nhave order-of-magnitude-compressed margin distributions (std\n≈0.009–0.03 vs ≈0.06–0.12 for the strong encoders), so\nthe fixed band covers most of their mass and the near-tie\nfraction is meaningful only for the strong encoders. This\nnear-tie band captures ~5.4–8.6 % of queries for the strong\ngeneric single encoders (ECAPA-TDNN, CAM++, ReDimNet;\nanimeva ≈1.9 %; full margin distributions in Fig. 2, each panel\nscaled to its own margin range). Across all encoders, hubness\n— the high-dimensional bias in which a few speakers become\nthe nearest neighbor of disproportionately many utterances —\nis consistently positive (k-occurrence skewness 1.4–3.6). The\nnominal permutation test gives p ≈ 0.005 at the B = 200\nfloor of 1/201, so we report it as exploratory/descriptive:\np ≈ 0.006 under Benjamini–Hochberg [64] but only p ≈ 0.07\nunder the stricter Holm correction [65] across our 16-test family (10 per-encoder hubness tests + 3 confusion-graph structure\ntests × 2 encoders), i.e. it does not survive Holm. WavLMbase-plus-sv scores poorly at raw cosine (rank-1 27 %), most\nlikely from representation anisotropy and/or our pooling of its\noutput (it partly recovers under centering), so we treat it as a\nlower bound, not the model’s true performance. We therefore\ntreat WavLM-base-plus-sv and the JP-HuBERT layermean as diagnostic probes, not tuned speaker-verification\nsystems (the latter a self-supervised representation without a\nverification head): they span the representation space, but the\nfloor and hubness claims of Sections IV-B and IV-C rest on\nthe properly-configured verification encoders (ECAPA-TDNN,\nCAM++, ReDimNet, animeva) and their ensembles: a hubness\nor floor figure on a 27 %-rank-1 embedding is not, on its own,\nevidence about well-trained encoders.\n\nB. The misidentification floor survives calibration, ensembling, and discriminative re-ranking\nThe floor is not a bad threshold; it is geometry. To prove\nthat, we separate what a threshold can move from what it\ncannot, reporting two identification-scale quantities. The first\nis the closed-set rank-1 misidentification rate (misID): the\nfraction of queries whose single nearest neighbor across the\ngallery belongs to a different speaker (equivalently, margin\nSsame − Sdiff < 0). Because every query’s true speaker is\nenrolled and there is no reject option, this is a closed-set\ntop-1 error (misID = 1 − rank-1), used deliberately as the\nranking-quality summary that no monotone recalibration can\nchange. The second is the 1 : N EER: treating “Is the\nquery’s top-scoring speaker the true speaker?” as a threshold\ndetector — which does carry a reject option — we sweep\nthe operating score and report the EER. This reject-capable,\nopen-set-flavored metric is distinct from the pairwise speakerverification EER. The evaluation is restricted to the codechomogeneous subset of agency audio (official agency sources,\nall MP3, freelance/YouTube-derived excluded; this guarantees codec homogeneity only — not same-studio or samemicrophone conditions; Sections IV-C and VII), with speakerlevel bootstrap 95 % confidence intervals (CIs). We report all\n10 encoders (Table II). The two diagnostic probes (WavLM,\nJP-HuBERT) are excluded from the floor claim (Section IV-A).\nTakeaway: AS-norm roughly halves the 1 : N EER and\ncollapses hubness, but closed-set misID falls only modestly\n(ensemble SV-4 5.1 % → 4.4 %). This asymmetry is exactly\nwhat the metric identities predict: AS-norm’s test-side term is\na monotone per-query shift that cannot reorder neighbors, and\nits enrollment-side term reorders them only weakly (rank-1\nimproves +0.3 to +3.9 pp, most for the weaker encoders, e.g.,\njxvector +3.9, x-vector +2.9), so calibration-invariance here\nis structural, not a finding. The load-bearing test is whether the\nfloor survives discriminative re-ranking that genuinely reorders neighbors: LDA, WCCN, and a two-covariance PLDA\nlog-likelihood ratio [20], train and test speakers are disjoint.\nTwo back-end details keep the test fair (Appendix A): LDA is\nrun as a genuine dimensionality reducer, since a full-rank LDA\ncoincides with WCCN under cosine, and the ensembles are\n\n\f6\n\nFig. 2. Identification-margin distributions across the eight encoders and two ensembles: the signed margin Ssame − Sdiff per query; the mass near zero is\nthe near-tie band of Section IV-A. Each panel is scaled to its own margin range, so the fixed |margin| < 0.02 band appears wider in the compressed-margin\npanels (x-vector, jxvector, WavLM).\nTABLE II\nR AW → AS- NORM EFFECT PER ENCODER ( RANK -1 %, 1 : N EER %, CLOSED - SET MIS ID %, k- OCCURRENCE HUBNESS SKEW ), ON THE\nCODEC - HOMOGENEOUS AGENCY SUBSET. AS- NORM ROUGHLY HALVES THE threshold-placement ERROR (1 : N EER) AND COLLAPSES HUBNESS , BUT\nTHE ranking ERROR ( MIS ID) FALLS ONLY MODESTLY — THE RESIDUAL FLOOR . (T HE 1 : N EER HERE IS A mated, MAX - OVER - GALLERY\nTOP -1- COMPETITOR CHARACTERISTIC , NOT COMPARABLE TO A PAIRWISE VERIFICATION EER; SEE A PPENDIX A. T HE RAW →AS- NORM COMPARISON\nIS WITHIN - ENCODER AND UNAFFECTED . B OOTSTRAP CI S IN A PPENDIX TABLE VIII.)\nEncoder\nx-vector\nECAPA-TDNN\nCAM++\nReDimNet-b2\njxvector\nanimeva\nensemble SV-4\nensemble all-6\nWavLM (diagnostic)\nJP-HuBERT (diagnostic)\n\nRank-1 (raw→AS)\n\n1:N EER (raw→AS)\n\nmisID (raw→AS)\n\nHubness (raw→AS)\n\n77.5 → 80.4\n85.7 → 87.4\n91.8 → 93.3\n92.2 → 93.2\n65.9 → 69.8\n97.5 → 97.8\n94.8 → 95.6\n94.4 → 95.1\n23.5 → 24.2\n61.0 → 64.3\n\n32.0 → 23.6\n27.0 → 15.9\n18.7 → 10.3\n17.4 → 9.8\n44.2 → 32.8\n10.1 → 3.9\n15.6 → 7.0\n17.3 → 7.6\n60.4 → 71.0\n43.4 → 37.0\n\n22.5 → 19.6\n14.3 → 12.6\n8.2 → 6.7\n7.8 → 6.8\n34.1 → 30.2\n2.5 → 2.2\n5.1 → 4.4\n5.5 → 4.9\n76.5 → 75.8\n39.0 → 35.7\n\n3.62 → 0.70\n2.18 → 0.80\n1.82 → 0.78\n1.45 → 0.83\n1.45 → 0.43\n0.90 → 0.86\n1.57 → 1.07\n1.61 → 1.02\n1.41 → 0.34\n1.91 → 0.45\n\nreduced by principal component analysis (PCA) [66] before\nPLDA. We report pairwise-trial EER and the minimum and\nactual calibrated log-likelihood-ratio costs (minCllr , actCllr ;\ntheir gap is the calibration loss, Appendix A). All columns\nare averaged over three speaker-disjoint splits (±std) with\na shared split-generation scheme; the misID column is a\ndeterministic full-gallery quantity per split, so its cosine →\nLDA → WCCN → PLDA progression within a row is directly\ninterpretable, while the pairwise EER/minCllr /actCllr columns\nuse independently seeded sampled trials and are comparable\nin trend, not trial-for-trial. All Table III values are over\nthe N = 497 evaluation-half speakers, not the ~1,100-\n\nspeaker full gallery of Table II. This gallery-size difference\nitself lowers misID, so the AS-norm-4.4 %-to-PLDA-2.6 %\nensemble drop mixes a back-end effect with an N effect; the\nfixed-N back-end effect is cosine 3.9 % → PLDA 2.6 % within\nTable III.\nPer-split std on the PLDA misID is ≤0.5 pp for every\nencoder, and speaker-level bootstrap 95 % CIs (1,000 resamples over eval speakers) are tight and mutually wellseparated: ensemble SV-4 2.6 % [2.45, 2.82], animeva 1.4 %\n[1.30, 1.55], ECAPA-TDNN 9.0 % [8.53, 9.50]. jxvector is a\nrevealing anomaly: its pairwise EER improves under PLDA\nShell cwd was reset to /inspire/qb-ilm/project/video-generation/chenxie-25019/hyr/iHateTheWorld555.github.io", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "f154d6d5-43c7-4ae8-9b50-952e770c6f4c", "uuid": "a8f1fe49-6154-4491-8db8-54177c485261", "timestamp": "2026-07-20T09:24:08.173Z", "tool_use_result": {"stdout": "is one example. Our main results use centering and AS-norm,\nbut we also ran a systematic comparison of these methods\n(cf. [36]): on the same query→centroid rank-1 protocol, comparing raw cosine, centering, CSLS (k=10), empirical mutual\nproximity [33], and NICDM (k=10) across four encoders\n(ECAPA-TDNN, animeva, WavLM, SV-4; animeva is our\ndomain-matched Japanese voice-actor ECAPA-TDNN, defined\nin Section III), no method improves misidentification by more\nthan ~0.3 points over raw cosine (local scaling hurts, by up\nto 5.8 points), and even mutual proximity — which flattens\nthe hub structure best (e.g. animeva k-occurrence skewness\n0.75→0.28) — leaves misidentification essentially unchanged.\nHubness can be reduced while the error floor does not move:\ndirect evidence that the floor is a property of the geometry,\nnot an artifact of hubness. Our claim is that a floor remains\nafter these standard reductions, not that the reductions are\nineffective.\nVoice privacy/anonymization. Our defensive setting is adjacent to speaker anonymization and voice privacy work [37],\nwhich deliberately suppresses speaker identity. We measure\nthe converse: how reliably can identity be attributed to a\nsynthetic clone?\nAnti-spoofing and spoofing-aware speaker verification\n(SASV). ASVspoof [38], [39] addresses detection of synthetic\nand spoofed speech, with tandem CM–ASV operation assessed\nby the tandem detection cost function (t-DCF) [40]; SASV\n[41] integrates these countermeasures with speaker verification, and the latest edition, ASVspoof 5 [42], folds SASV\nevaluation into the challenge at crowdsourced scale. The\nclosest existing resource to our threat setting is SpoofCeleb\n[43], which trains 23 text-to-speech (TTS) systems on in-thewild speech of 1,251 real VoxCeleb1 speakers and benchmarks\ndeepfake detection and SASV against that real enrolled pop-\n\nulation — still as a per-trial binary decision. A known weakness: countermeasures generalize poorly to unseen synthesis\nmethods [44]. Our task — attributing a clone to a real speaker’s\nidentity in an open set — extends SASV’s target/non-targetplus-spoof binary decision to 1 : N -way attribution. A twoparty dispute in which the suspected target actor is already\nnamed may reduce to 1 : 1 verification; even then, the\nsame real-synthetic shift, calibration-transfer, and per-speaker\nthreshold-spread problems apply (Sections IV-B and IV-D).\nWe adopt the more general 1 : N framing, subsuming the\nscreening use case — matching audio of unknown origin\nagainst a roster — that motivates this paper. This 1 : N\ndirection distinguishes our study from the known vulnerability\nof 1 : 1 verification to cloned audio (an impostor clone falsely\naccepted against its claimed target): our object is not threshold\nplacement but which of N real actors a clone is attributed to,\nand a floor on that decision that survives discriminative reranking. Existing large-gallery open-set identification benchmarks [45] target the general population; our contribution\nis that the difficulty and the attribution floor are driven by\nthe domain-intrinsic inter-speaker proximity and intra-speaker\nstyle range of the trained professional voices, which are largely\nabsent in such corpora.\nDeepfake source attribution. A separate line of work attributes generated audio to the model that produced it (vocoder\nfingerprints [46], source tracing [47]), and the recent sourceverification wave asks whether two synthetic tracks share a\ngenerator (SV-inspired but generator-level) [48]. All of this\nis generator/model attribution; at the speaker level, Cai et\nal. [49] show the source speaker behind a voice-conversion\nattack remains identifiable from the converted audio. Our\nquestion is orthogonal to both: which target real actor a\nsingle clone is attributed to, over a roster of real speakers.\nWe do not evaluate source-attribution methods; as a side\nobservation, Section IV-D reports that in a speaker-embedding\nspace, clustering by synthesizer is weak relative to clustering\nby speaker — we make no claim about what dedicated sourceattribution methods can achieve.\nFairness in speaker recognition. Demographic disparities\nin speaker recognition are documented [50]. We show a gender\ndisparity consistent with originating in the encoder’s training\ndomain and language, and removed by a domain-matched\nmodel.\nJapanese/voice-actor speech. For controls and a domainmatched encoder, we use JVS [21], Common Voice [22],\nJTubeSpeech [51], and animeva [52], an ECAPA-TDNN\ntrained on Japanese voice-actor speech (“animeva” is our\nshorthand, defined in Section III). For clone generation, we\nuse the zero-shot voice-conversion model Seed-VC [53] (v2\nrelease; a conditional-flow-matching (CFM) path with an\nautoregressive component, official default AR/CFM checkpoints, 30 sampling steps), the zero-shot TTS system GPTSoVITS [54] (run reference-only, no per-speaker fine-tuning),\nwhich spans two architecture lines — an incremental\nv1/v2 line with a high-fidelity v2ProPlus refinement, and\na newer reference-faithful v3/v4 line — each run with\nits official pretrained checkpoint pair (v1: s2G488k.pth,\nv2: s2G2333k.pth, v2ProPlus: s2Gv2ProPlus.pth, v3:\n\n\f4\n\ns2Gv3.pth, v4: s2Gv4.pth, with the corresponding default text-to-semantic (T2S) models), and the zero-shot TTS\nsystem Irodori-TTS [55] (Irodori-TTS-500M-v3, with the\nSemantic-DACVAE-Japanese-32dim codec [56]) — the latter\ntwo are public systems without academic papers, selected\nas representative Japanese-capable zero-shot synthesis; their\nfidelity is verified internally via the speaker-similarity measurements in Section IV-D, and because these systems evolve\nrapidly, exact model IDs and commits are released with the\nprovenance records of Section VI.\nIII. DATA AND PIPELINE\nRegistry (Phase 0a). We archive the seigura.com voiceactor directory [57] (声優名鑑, the Seiyu Grand Prix directory; operator Imagica Infos Co., Ltd.; URL and access dates\nin the references and provenance log). It lists 1,839 speaker\nentries across 255 agencies (1,838 distinct normalized names\n— one name maps to two entries; Section VII dedup), with\neach actor’s name, agency, and credited works, but no audio.\nThis registry is the denominator for our coverage. Every fetch\nis logged with its provenance (URL, UTC timestamp, SHA256).\nAudio (Phase 0b). We collect agency audio through peragency adapters — each agency’s site exposes samples differently, so each needs its own scraper: we enumerate the\ntalent roster, download each talent’s published samples (multiple speaking styles per talent), and match them back to\nregistry actors by normalized name. Adapters exist for the\n45 highest-actor-count agencies — ~18 % of the 255 registry\nagencies but ~64 % of registry actors, because agency size is\nheavily skewed; the remaining ~82 % are a long tail of a few\nactors each, left un-adapted at the manual per-site cost of a\nnew adapter (hence a selection bias toward larger agencies,\nSection VII). For freelance actors we use identity-verified\nofficial personal sites and official YouTube channels. “Agencyaffiliated” means having a registry agency field other than\n“freelance” (a one-person agency counts). This yields 1,103\nagency-affiliated actors (7,128 files) plus 71 freelance actors\n(277 files) — 1,174 actors in total.\nPreprocessing (Phase 0c). We standardize everything to\n16 kHz mono, remove silence with energy-based voice-activity\ndetection (VAD; librosa [58] effects.split, threshold\n30 dB below the reference level), and split into consecutive\nfixed 4 s windows, retaining a trailing remainder only if ≥3 s\n(so segments span 3–4 s) — the cut boundaries are mechanical,\nunrelated to sentence boundaries; speaker embeddings capture\nidentity content-independently, and the same segmentation is\napplied to every encoder and control population, so comparisons remain fair. 24 source files failed decoding or were\nemptied by VAD, and speakers left with zero usable segments\nwere dropped, giving a final corpus of 56,568 segments /\n1,168 speakers (1,103 agency + 65 freelance) / ~63 h. Each\nsegment carries a provenance back-pointer to its source and a\nrecording_source label. Coverage against the registry is\n1,168/1,839 = 63.5 %. The 671 uncollected actors are mostly\naffiliated with smaller agencies for which no scraper adapter\nwas built (511 actors — we built adapters for 45 of the\n\nregistry’s 255 agencies), plus freelance sources that could not\nbe captured (e.g. embedded players); this agency-side selection\nbias is discussed under generalization limits in Section VII.\nEncoders. The six base encoders are: x-vector [24] and\nECAPA-TDNN [25] (both English / VoxCeleb); WavLM-baseplus-sv [26] (English self-supervised model with a verification head); CAM++ [28] (Chinese; ModelScope checkpoint\ntrained on ~200k Mandarin speakers); ReDimNet-b2 [29]\n(English); and a layer-mean of Japanese HuBERT [59] (a\nJapanese self-supervised probe trained on the ReazonSpeech\nTV-broadcast corpus [60]). For language/domain controls,\nwe add two Japanese speaker verification models, referred\nto throughout by short names of our own: jxvector (the\nxvector_jtubespeech model, trained on JTubeSpeech)\n[61] and animeva (the anime_speaker_embedding\nmodel, an ECAPA-TDNN trained on ~989 Japanese voice\nactors) [52]; an overlap audit by name-matching against its\ntraining set’s published Visual Novel Database (VNDB) [62]\nvoice-actor metadata (Section IV-E) finds 21 % of our corpus\nin its training set, but its advantage holds on the heldout 79 %. animeva shares the ECAPA-TDNN architecture;\nthroughout, “ECAPA-TDNN” unqualified denotes the generic\nEnglish/VoxCeleb model, and the domain-matched model\nis always “animeva”. The two ensembles use embeddinglevel fusion: we concatenate each model’s L2-normalized\nembedding and renormalize, so the cosine similarity of the\nconcatenated vector equals the mean of the per-model cosine\nsimilarities (SV-4 bundles the four verification models; all-6\nbundles all six). This is deliberately a simple mean-pooling\nbaseline, not a novel fusion method — one of the mitigations\nwe test. Stronger fusion does not lower the floor, so we keep\nthe simple fixed-weight mean-pool (Table VII).\nLegal/ethics. Collection and analysis were conducted entirely within Japan under Article 30-4 (information analysis)\nof the Japanese Copyright Act [63], subject to that Article’s\nproviso, which we assess in Section VI; no audio is redistributed, and the clones are used only for the measurements in\nthis paper (no distribution, service offering, or impersonation;\nSection VI, including other jurisdictions).\nIV. R ESULTS\nA. Raw geometry: high accuracy, thin margins\nThe strong encoders look excellent, which is exactly the\nproblem: high rank-1 accuracy coexists with a large mass\nof queries decided by a hair. Table I reports raw-cosine\ngeometry across all eight encoders and the two embeddinglevel ensembles. Rank-1 accuracy — the fraction of queries\nwhose nearest neighbor is the correct speaker — is high\nfor the strong encoders (CAM++ and ReDimNet at 92.6 %,\nensembles at ~95 %, domain-matched animeva at 97.3 %), and\nevery encoder exhibits positive k-occurrence hubness skew.\nThe confound and control-population comparisons (Section IV-C) focus on representative encoders spanning the\nweak/strong and generic/domain-matched extremes (generic\nECAPA-TDNN, domain-matched animeva, SV-4 ensemble).\nEven at high rank-1 accuracy, many queries are decided by\na thin margin. Define the critical margin as the fraction of\n\n\f5\n\nTABLE I\nR AW- COSINE GEOMETRY PER ENCODER AND ENSEMBLE ( NO NORMALIZATION ): RANK -1 IDENTIFICATION ACCURACY, MISIDENTIFICATION RATE\n( MARGIN < 0), AND k- OCCURRENCE HUBNESS SKEW. T HIS IS A closed-set SETTING ( EVERY QUERY ’ S TRUE SPEAKER IS ENROLLED , NO REJECT OPTION );\nRANK -1 COUNTS STRICTLY- POSITIVE - MARGIN QUERIES AND MIS ID STRICTLY- NEGATIVE , SO MIS ID = 1 − RANK -1 up to zero-margin ties — WHICH\nFALL IN NEITHER AND ACCOUNT FOR THE SMALL ≤0.2 PERCENTAGE - POINT ( PP ) SHORTFALL IN THE ENSEMBLE ROWS . T HE TWO COLUMNS ARE\nCOMPLEMENTARY VIEWS OF THE SAME QUANTITY, SHOWN TOGETHER FOR READABILITY. T HE REJECT- CAPABLE OPERATING METRICS — STILL MATED ,\nI . E . NOT NON - TARGET- TESTED — ARE THE 1 : N EER OF S ECTION IV-B AND THE THRESHOLD - CONDITIONED CLONE ATTRIBUTION OF S ECTION IV-D.\nEncoder\n\nRank-1\n\nmisID\n\nHubness skew\n\nx-vector (EN/VoxCeleb)\nECAPA-TDNN (EN/VoxCeleb)\nWavLM-base-plus-sv (EN)\nCAM++ (ZH)\nReDimNet-b2 (EN)\nJP-HuBERT (layer-mean)\njxvector (JTubeSpeech)\nanimeva (JP voice-actor)\nensemble SV-4\nensemble all-6\n\n80.0 %\n86.7 %\n27.3 %\n92.6 %\n92.6 %\n65.9 %\n69.4 %\n97.3 %\n95.2 %\n95.0 %\n\n20.0 %\n13.3 %\n72.7 %\n7.4 %\n7.4 %\n34.1 %\n30.6 %\n2.7 %\n4.6 %\n4.9 %\n\n3.6\n2.5\n1.4\n2.2\n2.2\n1.9\n1.5\n2.2\n2.4\n2.2\n\nqueries for which |Ssame − Sdiff | < 0.02, where Ssame is the\nhighest-cosine score to the correct same speaker and Sdiff that\nto the most confusable different speaker. The 0.02 is a diagnostic cutoff on the raw-cosine margin scale; for the strong verification encoders, the conclusion is stable across cutoffs 0.005–\n0.05 (protocol in Appendix A). The absolute cutoff is not\ncomparable across encoders: x-vector, jxvector, and WavLM\nhave order-of-magnitude-compressed margin distributions (std\n≈0.009–0.03 vs ≈0.06–0.12 for the strong encoders), so\nthe fixed band covers most of their mass and the near-tie\nfraction is meaningful only for the strong encoders. This\nnear-tie band captures ~5.4–8.6 % of queries for the strong\ngeneric single encoders (ECAPA-TDNN, CAM++, ReDimNet;\nanimeva ≈1.9 %; full margin distributions in Fig. 2, each panel\nscaled to its own margin range). Across all encoders, hubness\n— the high-dimensional bias in which a few speakers become\nthe nearest neighbor of disproportionately many utterances —\nis consistently positive (k-occurrence skewness 1.4–3.6). The\nnominal permutation test gives p ≈ 0.005 at the B = 200\nfloor of 1/201, so we report it as exploratory/descriptive:\np ≈ 0.006 under Benjamini–Hochberg [64] but only p ≈ 0.07\nunder the stricter Holm correction [65] across our 16-test family (10 per-encoder hubness tests + 3 confusion-graph structure\ntests × 2 encoders), i.e. it does not survive Holm. WavLMbase-plus-sv scores poorly at raw cosine (rank-1 27 %), most\nlikely from representation anisotropy and/or our pooling of its\noutput (it partly recovers under centering), so we treat it as a\nlower bound, not the model’s true performance. We therefore\ntreat WavLM-base-plus-sv and the JP-HuBERT layermean as diagnostic probes, not tuned speaker-verification\nsystems (the latter a self-supervised representation without a\nverification head): they span the representation space, but the\nfloor and hubness claims of Sections IV-B and IV-C rest on\nthe properly-configured verification encoders (ECAPA-TDNN,\nCAM++, ReDimNet, animeva) and their ensembles: a hubness\nor floor figure on a 27 %-rank-1 embedding is not, on its own,\nevidence about well-trained encoders.\n\nB. The misidentification floor survives calibration, ensembling, and discriminative re-ranking\nThe floor is not a bad threshold; it is geometry. To prove\nthat, we separate what a threshold can move from what it\ncannot, reporting two identification-scale quantities. The first\nis the closed-set rank-1 misidentification rate (misID): the\nfraction of queries whose single nearest neighbor across the\ngallery belongs to a different speaker (equivalently, margin\nSsame − Sdiff < 0). Because every query’s true speaker is\nenrolled and there is no reject option, this is a closed-set\ntop-1 error (misID = 1 − rank-1), used deliberately as the\nranking-quality summary that no monotone recalibration can\nchange. The second is the 1 : N EER: treating “Is the\nquery’s top-scoring speaker the true speaker?” as a threshold\ndetector — which does carry a reject option — we sweep\nthe operating score and report the EER. This reject-capable,\nopen-set-flavored metric is distinct from the pairwise speakerverification EER. The evaluation is restricted to the codechomogeneous subset of agency audio (official agency sources,\nall MP3, freelance/YouTube-derived excluded; this guarantees codec homogeneity only — not same-studio or samemicrophone conditions; Sections IV-C and VII), with speakerlevel bootstrap 95 % confidence intervals (CIs). We report all\n10 encoders (Table II). The two diagnostic probes (WavLM,\nJP-HuBERT) are excluded from the floor claim (Section IV-A).\nTakeaway: AS-norm roughly halves the 1 : N EER and\ncollapses hubness, but closed-set misID falls only modestly\n(ensemble SV-4 5.1 % → 4.4 %). This asymmetry is exactly\nwhat the metric identities predict: AS-norm’s test-side term is\na monotone per-query shift that cannot reorder neighbors, and\nits enrollment-side term reorders them only weakly (rank-1\nimproves +0.3 to +3.9 pp, most for the weaker encoders, e.g.,\njxvector +3.9, x-vector +2.9), so calibration-invariance here\nis structural, not a finding. The load-bearing test is whether the\nfloor survives discriminative re-ranking that genuinely reorders neighbors: LDA, WCCN, and a two-covariance PLDA\nlog-likelihood ratio [20], train and test speakers are disjoint.\nTwo back-end details keep the test fair (Appendix A): LDA is\nrun as a genuine dimensionality reducer, since a full-rank LDA\ncoincides with WCCN under cosine, and the ensembles are\n\n\f6\n\nFig. 2. Identification-margin distributions across the eight encoders and two ensembles: the signed margin Ssame − Sdiff per query; the mass near zero is\nthe near-tie band of Section IV-A. Each panel is scaled to its own margin range, so the fixed |margin| < 0.02 band appears wider in the compressed-margin\npanels (x-vector, jxvector, WavLM).\nTABLE II\nR AW → AS- NORM EFFECT PER ENCODER ( RANK -1 %, 1 : N EER %, CLOSED - SET MIS ID %, k- OCCURRENCE HUBNESS SKEW ), ON THE\nCODEC - HOMOGENEOUS AGENCY SUBSET. AS- NORM ROUGHLY HALVES THE threshold-placement ERROR (1 : N EER) AND COLLAPSES HUBNESS , BUT\nTHE ranking ERROR ( MIS ID) FALLS ONLY MODESTLY — THE RESIDUAL FLOOR . (T HE 1 : N EER HERE IS A mated, MAX - OVER - GALLERY\nTOP -1- COMPETITOR CHARACTERISTIC , NOT COMPARABLE TO A PAIRWISE VERIFICATION EER; SEE A PPENDIX A. T HE RAW →AS- NORM COMPARISON\nIS WITHIN - ENCODER AND UNAFFECTED . B OOTSTRAP CI S IN A PPENDIX TABLE VIII.)\nEncoder\nx-vector\nECAPA-TDNN\nCAM++\nReDimNet-b2\njxvector\nanimeva\nensemble SV-4\nensemble all-6\nWavLM (diagnostic)\nJP-HuBERT (diagnostic)\n\nRank-1 (raw→AS)\n\n1:N EER (raw→AS)\n\nmisID (raw→AS)\n\nHubness (raw→AS)\n\n77.5 → 80.4\n85.7 → 87.4\n91.8 → 93.3\n92.2 → 93.2\n65.9 → 69.8\n97.5 → 97.8\n94.8 → 95.6\n94.4 → 95.1\n23.5 → 24.2\n61.0 → 64.3\n\n32.0 → 23.6\n27.0 → 15.9\n18.7 → 10.3\n17.4 → 9.8\n44.2 → 32.8\n10.1 → 3.9\n15.6 → 7.0\n17.3 → 7.6\n60.4 → 71.0\n43.4 → 37.0\n\n22.5 → 19.6\n14.3 → 12.6\n8.2 → 6.7\n7.8 → 6.8\n34.1 → 30.2\n2.5 → 2.2\n5.1 → 4.4\n5.5 → 4.9\n76.5 → 75.8\n39.0 → 35.7\n\n3.62 → 0.70\n2.18 → 0.80\n1.82 → 0.78\n1.45 → 0.83\n1.45 → 0.43\n0.90 → 0.86\n1.57 → 1.07\n1.61 → 1.02\n1.41 → 0.34\n1.91 → 0.45\n\nreduced by principal component analysis (PCA) [66] before\nPLDA. We report pairwise-trial EER and the minimum and\nactual calibrated log-likelihood-ratio costs (minCllr , actCllr ;\ntheir gap is the calibration loss, Appendix A). All columns\nare averaged over three speaker-disjoint splits (±std) with\na shared split-generation scheme; the misID column is a\ndeterministic full-gallery quantity per split, so its cosine →\nLDA → WCCN → PLDA progression within a row is directly\ninterpretable, while the pairwise EER/minCllr /actCllr columns\nuse independently seeded sampled trials and are comparable\nin trend, not trial-for-trial. All Table III values are over\nthe N = 497 evaluation-half speakers, not the ~1,100-\n\nspeaker full gallery of Table II. This gallery-size difference\nitself lowers misID, so the AS-norm-4.4 %-to-PLDA-2.6 %\nensemble drop mixes a back-end effect with an N effect; the\nfixed-N back-end effect is cosine 3.9 % → PLDA 2.6 % within\nTable III.\nPer-split std on the PLDA misID is ≤0.5 pp for every\nencoder, and speaker-level bootstrap 95 % CIs (1,000 resamples over eval speakers) are tight and mutually wellseparated: ensemble SV-4 2.6 % [2.45, 2.82], animeva 1.4 %\n[1.30, 1.55], ECAPA-TDNN 9.0 % [8.53, 9.50]. jxvector is a\nrevealing anomaly: its pairwise EER improves under PLDA", "stderr": "\nShell cwd was reset to /inspire/qb-ilm/project/video-generation/chenxie-25019/hyr/iHateTheWorld555.github.io", "interrupted": false, "isImage": false, "noOutputExpected": false}}
